@techreport{Vidotto2014,
abstract = {We investigate how the observed large-scale surface magnetic fields of low-mass stars (∼0.1-2 M), reconstructed through Zeeman-Doppler imaging (ZDI), vary with age t, rotation and X-ray emission. Our sample consists of 104 magnetic maps of 73 stars, from accreting pre-main sequence to main-sequence objects (1 Myr t 10 Gyr). For non-accreting dwarfs we empirically find that the unsigned average large-scale surface field |B V || is related to age as t −0.655±0.045. This relation has a similar dependence to that identified by Skumanich (1972), used as the basis for gyrochronology. Likewise, our relation could be used as an age-dating method ("magnetochronology"). The trends with rotation we find for the large-scale stellar magnetism are consistent with the trends found from Zeeman broadening measurements (sensitive to large-and small-scale fields). These similarities indicate that the fields recovered from both techniques are coupled to each other, suggesting that small-and large-scale fields could share the same dynamo field generation processes. For the accreting objects, fewer statistically significant relations are found, with one being a correlation between the unsigned magnetic flux $\Phi$ V and P rot. We attribute this to a signature of star-disc interaction, rather than being driven by the dynamo.},
